In small amounts, alcoholic drinks trigger a drop of your blood pressure as they dilate blood vessels. However, be careful; more than one or two drinks a day will have the opposite effect. If you don\'t normally drink alcohol, you shouldn\'t start it as a way of lowering blood pressure.
Even if it is Happy Hour, try to refrain from drinking too much alcohol.
Monitoring your blood pressure over time is one of the best health self-tracking initiatives that you can take. Blood pressure is a great indicator of your body’s health.
Take your blood pressure when you are comfortable, relaxed, and in a quiet environment. Try to do it around the same time each day.
That\'s it. Now is the time you chose to measure your BP.

For those with hypertension a supplement of Calcium can have a positive, yet modest, impact. However, if you combine it with a low-fat, fruit and vegetable-rich diet, you can obtain a more significant drop of your BP.
Why not change your breakfast habits? If you prefer, pick another meal to have more milk, fruits and vegetables.
On average you eat 2-3 times too much salt. If your blood pressure is high, try to eat less salt. Avoid adding salt to your food and choose home made meals over processed foods.
Set this reminder before lunch and dinner to slow down on your salt intake.
Day by day, try to lower your salt intake.
These small changes in your daily routine will help you be more active, sleep better, lose weight and strengthen your heart.
Small changes to lead a healthier life
Caffeine harms your sleep quality, try to avoid drinking coffee, tea or energy drinks 4 to 6 hours before your bedtime. About half of the caffeine you consume at 7pm is still in your body at 11pm.
Set a reminder half an hour before you\'re usually tempted to have a late afternoon coffee or tea. Then drink a glass of water instead.
From now on, try and avoid coffee and tea so they do not interfere with your sleep.
You\'ll sleep significantly better and feel more alert when you exercise 30 minutes or more during the day. Anything from a long walk to exercising on a treadmill will work.
Remember to stop exercising at least 90 minutes before going to bed to avoid raising your alertness, which could undermine your sleep.
Go for 30 minutes of exercise. It will help you sleep better tonight.
Be active to help you sleep
Make a habit of going to bed and waking up at the same time each day, and stick with it. Over time you\'ll fall asleep more easily and you will have more restful sleep too.
Create a reminder to be notified when you should go to bed in order get your 7-9 hours of sleep. Remember that regularity is what matters most.
Time to go to sleep. Regular sleep times will help you rest better.
Try to adopt fixed sleeping habits

Choose a ritual, like reading a book, practicing relaxing breathing techniques or drinking a cup of herbal tea. After repeating this pre-sleep ritual night after night, your brain will start interpreting them as \"Go to bed\" signals, preparing your body for sleep.
Depending on the length of your ritual, set this reminder 20 to 40 minutes before going to sleep.
It is time for your pre-sleep ritual.

Some hot herbal teas (like chamomile or valerian) have relaxant properties which can help you fall asleep. A hot drink also lowers your body\'s temperature, which helps falling asleep. Drinking a cup is also part of a great pre-sleep ritual.
Set this reminder approximately 20 minutes before your usual sleep time.
How about a hot herbal tea? It is a great pre-sleep ritual.
Breakfast helps reduce hunger until 4pm, which means you\'ll eat fewer snacks. Have a balanced breakfast with proteins, fruits and dairy.
Set this reminder approximately 20 minutes after you wake up if you are the type to skip breakfast.
You should eat breakfast. It will prevent an afternoon snack frenzy!

Fruits are healthy. They provide your body with some of the vitamins, minerals and fiber it needs. They also help prevent a large number of diseases. Have some fruit in the morning to prevent any afternoon hunger attack and help avoid snacking.
Set this reminder at a time when you are within easy reach of a fruit or right before your afternoon break.
Fruit is great for your health! Grab some now and eat it.

Log food to follow your calorie intake. Track activity too, to balance exercise and nutrition – a great way to manage your weight. Connect your account with your MyFitnessPal account to log your food.
Set reminders around the times you usually finish eating your breakfast, lunch and dinner. Once you are used to logging your food you can delete the reminders.
Did you track your meal? If not, remember to monitor your calorie-intake.
You should step on your scale regularly as you\'ll be more likely to achieve your weigh goal. Try to weigh-in between 2 and 7 times a week.
Once or twice a week is a good start. The best time to set this reminder is right after or before your morning shower.
Step on your scale now. When you weigh-in regularly you are more likely to achieve your weight goal.

Aim to drink about 6 to 8 glasses of fluid, preferably water, every day (more if it’s hot or if you are exercising). Try drinking a glass of water first when you feel hungry to check if you\'re not confusing thirst with hunger.
Set this reminder whenever you generally feel hungry between meals – in the middle of the afternoon for example.
Drink water to rehydrate your body, especially if you feel hungry and crave a snack.

Learn more about the Visceral Fat Index
What is the Visceral Fat Index?
Visceral fat is a type of fat that can be found around vital organs in the abdominal area (trunk). More precisely, visceral fat surrounds the stomach, liver, intestines and other organs.
This is the type of fat most linked to health problems.
Maintaining healthy levels of visceral fat can help reduce cardiovascular risks, high blood pressure and the onset of type 2 diabetes.
What’s the difference between visceral fat and subcutaneous fat?
Visceral fat and subcutaneous fat are two different types of fat.
Subcutaneous fat is a type of fat that is stored just under the skin. It\'s the fat you can easily pinch between your fingers.
However, visceral fat is located behind the abdominal muscles and cannot be seen. It surrounds the stomach, liver, intestines and other organs.
The level of visceral fat in the body is measured by what we call the Visceral Fat Index, which ranges from 1 (lowest) to 20 (highest).

A Visceral Fat Index from 1 to 5 (included) indicates you have a normal level of visceral fat. Continue monitoring your score over time to ensure it stays within the normal range. Regular activity can help reduce your visceral fat score.
A Visceral Fat Index from 5 to 20 indicates you have a high level of visceral fat. Implementing a healthy diet and frequent activity can help reduce the visceral fat score.
